{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fef24c3e-9657-4c1f-9a01-fd4eb9324eab","content":"The directory is empty, so I'll give you the configuration guidance directly.\n\nTo publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org, add these properties to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server over stdio</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <RepositoryUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</RepositoryUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|----------|---------|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the project as a dotnet tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users will invoke |\n| `OutputType` must be `Exe` | Tools must be executables |\n\n**Publishing steps:**\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_KEY --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Users install with:**\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's all that's needed — no special MCP-specific packaging is required since stdio transport just uses stdin/stdout on the resulting executable.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e5072131-75b8-4bbf-a62a-b80f8a82c074","outputTokens":477,"requestId":"2C07:2E6F9:2AC10A7:2F23F45:69FD3722"},"id":"024b835b-3eb8-4b8c-be9b-d639fab5b31b","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:06:51.785Z","parentId":"8c4ad2e3-0f54-42cf-888f-162ea23a231d"}
